commits.commitMessage:
Implement query mode for AT+WDSX command

1) Support for AT+WDSX?
2) Support for AT+WDSX=0,x

Resolves: LE-16207
Change-Id: I06ffd96996665c4d9667be6d872c6d73e261a88c
commits.subject: Implement query mode for AT+WDSX command

comments.message: In the code, I can only see AT+WDSX? implemented as part of this review. There is no update to the code block for type LE_ATSERVER_TYPE_PARA in WdsxCmdHandler(). Am I missing something or the parameter type is also implemented or already working?

Yes, the "set" mode (AT+WDSX=x,y[,z]) was already implemented and working, and undergone integration testing. 
This patch addresses the missing modes that weren't implemented before, in particular 
AT+WDSX?
and
AT+WDSX=0,y[,z] (disconnect command)
Can we also return the result code/text using LE_RESULT_TXT(result)?
Can you provide a sample output and does this manage more than one serverID if we connect to more than one? e.g. DM connected and EDM connected. Thx

+WDS* commands look like they only handle connecting to one server at a time, do we need to handle the case with multiple connections active?  I was thinking of modifying the output though so it would list all servers, but show active or not active.

E.g.

    +WDSX: 1,0
    +WDSX: 1000,1
    OK

commits.commitMessage:
[AVMS] Support +WDSI notification and handle +WDSR=4 for local update

Per requirement from Iskraemeco customer, we will support local update +WDSD.
We need to support +WDSI notifications and handle +WDSR=4 for local update.

Resolves: LE-16556 LE-16557
Related: QTI9X07TX-3884 QTI9X07TX-3885
Change-Id: I0657c94d269e6b0ab6ddd8943bb98dbb4ffdb9db
Signed-off-by: Tien Tra <TTra@sierrawireless.com>
commits.subject: [AVMS] Support +WDSI notification and handle +WDSR=4 for local update

comments.message: Should remove these states as they are not used.

This modifies the AVMS session state to SESSION_STATUS_PKG_DOWNLOADED and it is undesirable.
```
statusPtr->session = SESSION_STATUS_PKG_DOWNLOADED;
```

Can implement LE_AVC_LOCAL_INSTALL_PENDING to just send URC and avoid that.
To avoid any impact with AVMS, I think I will add the code here to send +WDSI directly
Should remove these states as they are not used.

The should be implemented per the FW update status retrieved from QMI:
https://issues.sierrawireless.com/browse/MOLRC9X07-374?focusedCommentId=8488217&page=com.atlassian.jira.plugin.system.issuetabpanels:comment-tabpanel#comment-8488217
- 6. Implement +WDSI URCs handling
This is reserved for future use. As FW team has not implemented this.
Should remove this state as it is not used.
Sorry, I will keep this definition as it is used in PA functions
Should remove these states as they are not used.
I will keep these definitions to report +WDSI: 14 and for future use
Should remove these states as they should be retrieved directly from QMI as mentioned above.
For now, I will keep these definitions. We will remove these in future when new implement is agreed with FW team

I think these external interfaces are not mandatory and should be avoided.
We can consider 2 separate flows of update - one initiated from OTA from AVMS, another initiated from +WDSD from MPSS.
Their state machines are independent and use fota partition as a common resource to write package.

For local download, the session is transient in a local session, MPSS should prevent simultaneous access to the fota partition. As mentioned, AirVantage takes precedence over +WDSD local download.

Hi Paul,

Patchset 5 removes unused functions and adds new +WDSI 12, 13 and 14. Please help to review again.

Thanks,
Tien.

Hi all,

This patch has been cherry-picked to 22.02-release-threadx branch. Please help to start review on this:

https://gerrit.legato/c/product/threadx/+/82597
https://gerrit.legato/c/Legato/Apps/AtAirVantage/+/82598
https://gerrit.legato/c/Legato/platformAdaptor/qmi/+/82599

We will back to this in future.

Thanks,
Tien.
Do not submit to master for now.  If needed going forward, will rework based on patches submitted to branch.
Comment removed by: Paul Chan; Reason: Corrected - pa_install_Local() is indeed implemented

This handler reports events from FW. It triggers nothing. Just send +WDSI URC. For:
1. Yes, we did. Please find in PA functions
2. FW will report it via QMI message
3. This will be handle in FW code. Legato just report events

Per the requirement, the local installation starts with AT+WDSR=4 and it should use QMI_SWI_M2M_FDT_CLOSE_REQ to initiate an update.

From https://issues.sierrawireless.com/browse/MOLRC9X07-374?focusedCommentId=8489054&page=com.atlassian.jira.plugin.system.issuetabpanels%3Acomment-tabpanel#comment-8489054 , the proposed handling is

Implement +WDSR=4 handling on Legato
1. Implement local install function pa_install_Local() (empty currently)
It may call pa_fwupdate_Install/ Qmi_FwupdateInstall() with a local_install flag as argument
2. Call to CloseFDT() / QMI_SWI_M2M_FDT_CLOSE_REQ with a new reason REASON_LOCAL_INSTALL instead of REASON_NORMAL,
3. and set a +WDSD NV flag on success
These are not required, where are these defined and why do we add these ?

Required from SE. To support +WDSI: 12. I also handle for +WDSI: 13. You can have quick look at install.h.
Again, these events will be reported by FW

As mentioned, there is already an existing flow in Legato to retrieve the update status. Why do we need to create another software flow to rely on QMI indication messages from MPSS ?

From https://issues.sierrawireless.com/browse/MOLRC9X07-374?focusedCommentId=8488217&page=com.atlassian.jira.plugin.system.issuetabpanels%3Acomment-tabpanel#comment-8488217 
Would you point 6 about "LE_AVC_LOCAL_INSTALL_COMPLETE and LE_AVC_LOCAL_INSTALL_FAILED" and explain why we cannot use that approach ?
This is our agreement with FW team. That FW will report these events. It depends on implement in FW. Legato just handles QMI messages then send +WDSI URC

I think I'm with Paul on this one -- instead of developing an entirely new QMI and PA, it would be better to slot this into the existing workflow for returning indications from modem to APSS.

To accelerate fix on RC76 we can use this as a temporary solution; but then it should go in the 22.02-release-threadx branch, not in master.

comments.message:
Please also update the doxygen document file: legato/apps/proprietary/atAirVantage/src/atAirVantage/doc/WDSS_cmdGuide.dox

@Stanley, don't we push this patch to a non-master branch first?

Also, this patch assumes customers will only run AT+WDSS=0 in this case, but isn't this because customers have run AT+WDSS=1,<APN>,<User>,<Cid> beforehand, and thus run AT+WDSS=0 to clear all these settings? So, I'm afraid if we don't implement/update the command to allow the format of AT+WDSS=1,<APN>,<User>,<Cid>, it might cause another customer bug in near future. 

This concern has been posted in Keith's email as well.
I updated with max parameters for this mode now is 5.

I am no sure which non-master branch I can use. And due to schedule is tight, I think in master branch can faster complete this function. Avoid any non-sync with master branch issue.

If you have any idea, I can move it to other branch.
After discussion, yes, master is fine. Thanks.

According to HL76 AT manual, there can be two possible output for AT+WDSS?, E.g.,
(1) When there's some configuration set previously,
    +WDSS: 0,"broadband",,1
    +WDSS: 1,0
    OK
(2) When there's no configuration set,
    OK
So, for the case that we only implement the dummy AT+WDSS=0, we shall follow case (2), which doesn't output anything, and thus this block of code seems not needed.

Hi, I got these values from AirPrime_HL76xx_AT_Commands_Interface_Guide_Rev13_0.pdf page 320, this document attached in ticket MOLRC9X07-374.

AT+WDSS=?
+WDSS: 0, 50,30,30,(1-5)
+WDSS: 1,(0-1)
OK
Will not add a dummy AT+WDSS=0 implementation to master.  Either needs proper implementation or nothing.

[AVMS] Add support level 4095 for +WDSI

For +WDSI=4095, SWI will support 128 (Bit 7/Event 17) and 2048 (Bit 11) as a dummy function
Return OK for +WDSI=4095 without making any changes to the device
Also support 512 (Bit 9), 1024 (Bit 10) as 4095 also contains these Bits.

Resolves: LE-16552
Related: QTI9X07TX-3880
Change-Id: I46cc304dacbdbf31bef4458a4d2d0e0bd44bc5bc
commits.subject: [AVMS] Add support level 4095 for +WDSI

comments.message: Looks good other than the one comment.
maybe, arrange them in their bit order?
What is the reason for this logic?  It seems like just updating SUPPORTED_IND_MASK should be enough, especially since below you set indPtr->level to origin_level.
Hi Chung, why you want to make sure bits 7, 9, 10, and 11 are cleared before writing to file, why don't you write what the value of level is?

Hi Vincent, it's because before this path, SUPPORTED_IND_MASK is not included this bits, so all of them is 0 when wrote to INDICATIONS_FILE. But in this path, if user enter these bits to 1, but we just want to create dummy function for them so I don't want to write them to INDICATIONS_FILE, it may cause unexpected error/behavior.

Hi Chung, then I think we shall not clear these bits before writing to INDICATIONS_FILE. We shall save whatever provided by customer/user if the command allows that, otherwise it is inconsistent when customer run AT+WDSI?. I think it's OK for now to implement them as dummy ones, the explanation is: we allow to set these indications but we don't generate these indications. I think saving them shouldn't cause any side effect, @Enoch.

commits.commitMessage:
Revert multiple changes re-introducing +WAMS handling in atAirVantage

This check-in reverts the following changes re-adding +WAMS handling in
atAirVantage.

Revert "WAMS verify always returns OK"
Revert "Change +WAMS prompt to >"
Revert "Re-introduce +WAMS handling in atAirVantage."

Reason for revert: +WAMS command still not working with factory process.

Reverted Changes:
I401f06cb5:LE-16514 - Re-disable +WAMS handling in FW.
Ic7233bc12:Move MK_CONFIG_ENABLE_WAMS to .sinc file
I016a7db59:WAMS verify always returns OK
Ie916903b4:Change +WAMS prompt to >
I9c3d4b0b4:Re-introduce +WAMS handling in atAirVantage.
I439a3bb36:Re-introduce le_avc_SetCredential back-end.
I0b09d8af5:Re-introduce changes to system definition.
Ia990ae590:Re-add le_avc API for passing credentials.

Change-Id: I750e9deda0556e83e66461864cd1b2e462524610
Resolves: LE-16514
Related: ALT1250-4481
commits.subject: Revert multiple changes re-introducing +WAMS handling in atAirVantage

commits.commitMessage:
Block EDM connection when AVC session is requested

The SIM reachability piggy-back mechanism attempts to make an EDM connection if a session has been opened. This affects the AVC session request since it starts an EDM session immediately one is requested. This patch will block the EDM connection if an AVC session has been requested.

Resolves: LE-16474
Change-Id: I9560a6bfffa8d4c7e6f8eacf485ae5f19bbf1b34
commits.subject: Block EDM connection when AVC session is requested

comments.message: Session already started, hence no need to set the global variable true

Is it the right approach? Personally I don't like usage of global variable when there is already a state machine running inside the avcDaemon. In most of the cases global variable can be replaced easily by a state machine state, which is much cleaner and less bug prone approach. Any reason why we aren't using avcDaemon state?

Let's assume we have to use global variable, then what will happen for the following usecase
1. User started a session by at+wdss=1,1
2. User again gave command at+wdss=1,1 (provided that previous session is already active)

I am suspecting IsAvcSessionProcessing's value will be true which isn't right.
For the time being, this seems ok. However, starting session from control app issue isn't resolved. Better to create a ticket which can be addressed later.

commits.commitMessage:
WAMS verify always returns OK

In the past, +WAMS in 'verify' mode would perform a simple string
compare between a stored WAMS credential and a command argument. Since
we have moved certain WAMS credentials into the IKS, it is no longer
possible to retrieve their raw values in order to perform the compare.
In order to avoid test or factory failures, this patch stubs out the
verification behaviour so that it always returns 'OK'. The validity of
the credentials is implicitly tested when a device attempts to connect
to a LwM2M bootstrap server.

Resolves: LE-16527
Change-Id: I016a7db59324090fbc09058ae36f9c0bf07e13dc
commits.subject: WAMS verify always returns OK

comments.message: change variable name to wamsDataModeCtx to match with renamed type?

why move the verification here when handling data in data mode? Will retrieval of the data from IKS be possible in future? If not, maybe just directly return OK in WamsSet() when in verify mode,otherwise, waiting for user to enter data but always return OK even when data is wrong doesn't make much sense.

Retrieval of a credential's raw value of from the IKS won't be possible, but perhaps another means of verification can be implemented (i.e. signing something). Of course I'm not aware of any plans to do that..

The real reason for doing things this way is so that the factory provisioning tool "sees" the same +WAMS flow as before. If we just return 'OK' immediately, it may cause the tool to trip up as it receives an 'OK' instead of '>'

commits.commitMessage:
Implement AT+WAMS handling in atAirVantage

This patch moves handling of the AT+WAMS command to atAirVantage.

Resolves: LE-16440
Change-Id: I549aab03c7e25f0dd0c42b47bbe2a2b0a18102ac
commits.subject: Implement AT+WAMS handling in atAirVantage

comments.message: Is this just a move of the file or is there anything else that was changed?
The only change is that instead of calling lwm2mcore_SetCredential() to save a credential, we now call the new le_avc API

commits.commitMessage:
Add DOTA diagnostics AT command

Any feature involving network is complicated to test, such as Delta
FOTA. Therefore, before using AVMS to test Delta FOTA, we want to test
it locally and do not have to deal with the unstable network
environment.

To test Delta FOTA locally, we need a way to flash a local delta package
to the FOTA partition, and a way to manipulate the FOTA cookie. We
already have the +WFWUPD command for flashing delta packages, so the
only thing left to be done is a new AT command for the rest of the
features.

In this patch, we implement the +WFOTACTL command, which can:
  * Set FOTA cookie
  * Clear FOTA cookie
  * Query FOTA cookie
  * Query the error number of the last Delta FOTA process
  * Query the log messages of the last Delta FOTA process

With both the +WFWUPD and +WFOTACTL commands, we can implement test
automation for the Delta FOTA feature.

Please notice that, you need to unlock before using the +WFOTACTL
command.

Resolves: LE-16442
Change-Id: Ibef90662dce088d8f13686e42f75e4b09f656835
commits.subject: Add DOTA diagnostics AT command

comments.message:
Why is it needed to undefine this first?  We are in the APPS_TX image here I think.

If nothing else, should have a comment.

The AT Unlock API is only used by the modem firmware, so it is very tricky to make this API available in Legato.

In ThreadX, the atuproto.h header will include unnecessary prototypes that will conflict with some existing prototypes in Legato, so we need to add some preprocessor logic to prevent the compiler errors.

I'll add comments to explain why we need such an ugly logic here.

comments.message: I'd rather this was just 10, or a constant called something like CONV_BASE.  Including 10 in the name of the constant loses the value of having a named constant.
Not necessary on a declaration in a header like this.
Please set your editor to automatically maintain a newline at the end of all text files.  POSIX compliant text files must end with a newline character.
Please always use braces for conditional blocks.
We already have liblegato functions for converting hexadecimal <-> binary.  See le_hex.h (included via legato.h).
Nice, I'll update my patch to use the pre-existing API.
I suggest declaring at least the key package and value buffers at function scope so that they can be accessed in the "cleanup" section.  They should be explicitly zeroed out after use.
I confirmed with Alex Jiang that the wrapping key is public so I think that it isn't a security issue to not zero out these buffers
Zero out the buffers here.  See, for example, https://www.gnu.org/software/libc/manual/html_node/Erasing-Sensitive-Data.html.
Similar comment about zeroing buffers here.
I'm not familiar enough with the IKS APIs to know if this should be zeroed as well, but please check.

This "package contains" the credential after it is encrypted by the IKS's wrapping key. It can only be decrypted by the corresponding private key which can't leave the IKS. Because of this I think we're OK not zeroing this buffer out.
I recommend using LE_FATAL() in this case.  Then there is no risk of a change in compiler flags  suddenly causing execution to proceed at this point.
Zero out this buffer when complete, as well.
This buffer should be zeroed at an appropriate point, as well.

commits.commitMessage:
[R2C] Implement SIM Reachability (EDM) feature

- New lwm2m object to support SIM Reachability
- AVC supports multiple instances of Objects 0 and 1
  (DM credentials/properties)
- AVC to be able to manage sessions with 2 (or more) DM servers
- Receive SIM APDU response from the modem FW and provide it
  to EDM server
- Device must provide to the Bootstrap server an indication for
  EDM support

Resolves: LE-14723 LE-14736 LE-14774 LE-14775 LE-15155
Change-Id: I03705147f4d80198a6e070e3a3ad7e1df5cb7dbe
commits.subject: [R2C] Implement SIM Reachability (EDM) feature

comments.message: Should this be just LE_WARN or LE_DEBUG than LE_ERROR?
Inline comment to specify the function's return values please.

Please see if we still need this code embraced within
#if LE_CONFIG_ENABLE_CONFIG_TREE #endif
Ditto: inline comment for return values.
You deemed it unnecessary to add descriptions of return values here?
We don't need this, as LE_ERROR() will provide it automatically, including line #

If result != LE_OK, then you'll skip the 2 back-to-back "if (LE_OK == result)" and go into the "else" underneath.
This flow is a bit weird. Please be sure that this is what you want.
why do we cast back and forth between uint8 -> char -> uint8? can this parameter just be uint8_t*?
This line is still long with __func__ not removed yet, as commented earlier.

Sorry Andrew, this got overlooked - I'll upload fix for both items you've pointed out. 
Also I've spotted couple other things in this file, that need to be fixed as well...

commits.commitMessage:
Fix various bugs related to SIM reachability

1) Provide server ID in +WDSI indication
2) Restrict connection to server ID 1000 (EDM) when connecting using +WDSX

Resolves: LE-15649 LE-15576
Change-Id: I851551fe1d904c66f3cb20a281e5d68377d5665a
commits.subject: Fix various bugs related to SIM reachability

commits.commitMessage:
Allow at+wdss=2,X to set unconfigured pdp context ID X

Originally, we allow at+wdss=2,X to set unconfigured pdp context ID X
on Master branch. There are some modifications on HL78 product branch
made to only allow at+wdss=2,X to set configured pdp context ID X. The
modification is ported from HL78 product branch to Master branch when
we port atAirVantage changes from HL78 to master (LE-13476). This change
causes some behavior change which is inconsistent with documentation.
So, remove the related change.

Resolves: LE-15296 LE-15389
Change-Id: I2f9c5914440a8e223a8712056baafe8c7fd6985f
commits.subject: Allow at+wdss=2,X to set unconfigured pdp context ID X

commits.commitMessage:
Clean up some warnings when logging is enabled.

A number of Legato variables and even functions are only used for
logging.  Clean up usage of these variables to avoid referencing them
if the corresponding logging is not enabled.

This is needed to avoid unused variable/function warnings on ThreadX
when logging is disabled.

Resolves: LE-14722
Change-Id: I33645e93413a3536dc3d1c70746f458f8b4727d3
commits.subject: Clean up some warnings when logging is enabled.

commits.commitMessage:
Resolve uninitialized buffer message in Klocwork

Klocwork throws an uninitialized buffer message for timers.  This
variable is actually initialized by le_avc_GetRetryTimers(), but
the message can easily be quieted by initializing timers before
making that call as well.

Resolves: LE-14722
Change-Id: I203f508ec1f65040f3295c7740309ba4463e1275
commits.subject: Resolve uninitialized buffer message in Klocwork

commits.commitMessage:
[AVMS] Notification +WDSI: 0 is absent

Issue Description:
When device is reset by at!reset or reboot job on AVMS server, the
unsolicited notification "+WDSI: 0" is absent after device startup.
It can be reproduced when ADB interface is enabled.

Root Cause:
When adb interface is enabled, more initialization works are required.
The time when usb is ready is longer than the time while ADB interface
is disabled.
Unsolicited notification "+WDSI: 0" can't be sent to modem interface
successfully before usb is ready.

Solution:
Send the +WDSI: 0 after usb is ready.

Resolves: LE-14597
Change-Id: I63f1ce0c632c4a6fa1651127ef2ad59098dcb754
Signed-off-by: Rinne Zhang <RiZhang@sierrawireless.com>
commits.subject: [AVMS] Notification +WDSI: 0 is absent

commits.commitMessage:
Resolve compiler error from bypassing initialization

ARM compiler complains about declaring and initializing variables
based on flow so this change moves declaration and initialization
to the start of function.

Resolves: LE-14339
Change-Id: I6def6edde936b0f55be60f2de7d53d7ebe27fa7f
commits.subject: Resolve compiler error from bypassing initialization

> Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

> I think that the best solution is like in uLegato.
> See LE-11118 and https://gerrit-legato/c/Legato/Apps/AtAirVantage/+/35030

I think supported level of AT+WDSI=<Level> are different in AT command guide documents for WP76xx and HL78XX.

In document "AirPrime - HL78xx - AT Commands Interface Guide - Rev3.0.pdf", it gives example of at+wdsi=? as below.
AT+WDSI=?
+WDSI: (0-127,256-383,4096-4223,4352-4479)
OK

But in document "4118047_WPx5xx-76xx-77xx AT Command Reference_r5.pdf", it lists supported level of AT+WDSI=<Level> as below.
Parameters:
<Level> (Unsolicited AirVantage Management Services notifications bit mask)
• Bit mask indicating which notifications to enable/disable entered as integer value
• Default: 0= No indications activated
• Bit value:
• 0=Indication deactivated
• 1=Indication activated
• Range: 0–8191. Add the values of each bit listed below. (See +WDSI (notification) on
page 251 for <Event> details.)

Patch Set 2: -Code-Review

As you want but I think that several levels are not supported in WP76

Patch Set 2:

FMO, unsupported or reserved bytes should remain 0. Why not change the AT documentation?

commits.commitMessage:
[AVMS] AT+WDSI = 8191 not supported

Issue Description:
AT+WDSI = 8191 not supported. AT response of AT+WDSI=? from WP7607
device is "+WDSI: (0-4479)". In AT command manual
"4118047_WPx5xx-76xx-77xx AT Command Reference_r6.pdf", for command
"AT+WDSI=<Level>", range of Level is 0–8191.

Root Cause:
In AT command manual, event 17, 19–22 and bit 11 are reserved
which means bits 7/9/10/11 are reserved and should remain 0,
document 4118047 and 2174152 should be updated along with codes.

Solution:
Change range of supported Level from (0-4479) to (0-127,256-383,
4096-4223,4352-4479).

Resolves: LE-11712 MOLWP9X07-216
Change-Id: I08623650a3189586ae9d92422e0dc9b9b163c74f
Signed-off-by: Rinne Zhang <RiZhang@sierrawireless.com>
commits.subject: [AVMS] AT+WDSI = 8191 not supported

commits.commitMessage:
Merge atAirvantage from uLegato to Master

uLegato tag is 18.09.2.ALT1250.rc6. Merged fixes are:

- Manage +WDSI: 11,0 notification
- +WDSI: 11 internal update
- Fix +WDSG command response for package donwload
- [+WDSI] Add new values for +WDSI: 11 notification
- Allow +WDSE command if not connected to AirVantage
- Fix Incorrect syntax in AT+WDSTPF? command response
- Support local FW install
- [AV] Add inline AT AirVantage documentation
- Create a new component for WDSTPF at command
- Add new AT commands to set and launch third party FOTA
- [AVMS] Fix +WDSC command
- Fix +WDSG notification after package download

Resolves: LE-12559
Change-Id: I8dd6dd7e4100b5f762eeafe805c2c8c0ff2cd8f5
commits.subject: Merge atAirvantage from uLegato to Master

commits.commitMessage:
Fix storing AT+WDSI command setting

Setting for +WDSI:0 wasn't stored in either memory or file. Hence,
AT+WDSI? returned old stale value after setting AT+WDSI=0. Also, the
old setting was loaded after device reboot as +WDSI:0 wasn't stored
in file.

Resolves: LE-8888
Change-Id: Ib8ea8309287f58ba89e9ce3fcc8fb50fdb5b4e45
commits.subject: Fix storing AT+WDSI command setting

comments.message: Don't you need to write to the file even when user is changing to NO indication as well?
Yes. This is what the ticket about. "NO indication" setting isn't stored in file. Hence it isn't persistent over restart and picked up the old settings
Might be best to use sizeof(level) ?
It might make sense to move this block which removes the handler to the bottom after writing to the indications file.
For NO_INDICATION handlers should be removed, however for any other case handler should be added.

commits.commitMessage:
Add support for +WDSI 11,1 and 11,2 events

Resolves: LE-8378
Change-Id: Id5eacd09ae782b5a0f2f74b4978a385d0b96d9b2
commits.subject: Add support for +WDSI 11,1 and 11,2 events

comments.message:
Can you confirm that for the moment, this is not supported
Only supported on single system products

The problem is that a bundle may be downloaded and stored in one or several partitions depending on its content. However, following the spec, WDSI:11,0 should be sent before start download.
Total size is not enough data to know if it will fit or not. We need to download the file first and parse it, to get the size of each component..
So when this value is used ? :)
I've discussed this with ADO, we'll create another ticket for the support of this
I believe this would be trigged when CERTIFICATION_KO is received, not on DOWNLOAD_FAILED. Could you 2xcheck please ?

+WDSI:11,2 is defined as follows
Corrupted firmware update package, did not store correctly. Reasons include (or example), mismatched CRCs between actual and expected, or signature check error

However, LWM2M error status is converted to AVC error status and there is a loss in information (see function ConvertFumoErrorCode in avcClient.c line 138)

Corrupted package => LE_AVC_ERR_BAD_PACKAGE
Failed validation => LE_AVC_ERR_SECURITY_FAILURE
Invalid URI, DL error, no suffisent memory (which is not supported) => LE_AVC_ERR_INTERNAL

Mayble I should exclude the case of LE_AVC_ERR_INTERNAL in this if statement?
ok, bad comment, CERTIFICATION_KO is mapped on +WDSI: 13 , not 11

commits.commitMessage:
Check parameters range and type

Resolves: LE-8338
Change-Id: I5da1b8ce43ef2cf26bbbad6e0773999f0790f572
commits.subject: Check parameters range and type

comments.message: Document the return codes of this function
isn't it obvious when you read the code?

Reading the code is one thing
Documenting it is another one :)

So what? All function headers should be documented, whatever the complexity of the function. I should be able to see at once what is returned, when and why, without having to read the code. This is called "documentation".

By the way the input parameters should be documented as well with ///< comments.

And you should use char* strPtr and int* valPtr to have homogeneous code throughout the file.

This a simple local function to convert a string into an integer. All the local functions aren't documented.
I document a function (using doxygen syntax) when it's api and will be exported (documentation) to some kind of a web page or something but here the code is straight forward.

I don't know what to say... This is a standard code documentation as it is done elsewhere in Legato.
Please don't ask me to do your code reviews if it is just to dismiss all my comments, it's a time loss for everyone.
This could be merged in test of line 69 ?

yes could be.

The idea here is to verify that strtol works as expected, ask for a long get a long, once a long is obtained check for int limits.
This could be merged with test of line 654 ?

UserConfig_t is an enum ==> int.
This avoids doing this HandleUserAgreement((UserConfig_t)config, userAgreement);

You don't consider the 'config' parameter as an int, otherwise you should use 0, 1, 2 in your switch/case and not CONFIG_xxx.
It doesn't hurt to use UserConfig_t (and bool BTW) for the parameters, it makes the function clearer.

a percentage progress is indicated in <Data> parameter.

commits.commitMessage:
Fix APN configuration strings lengths

Resolves: LE-7867
Change-Id: I0f30f7987c36ba79f0aa97f7974541c16011254a
commits.subject: Fix APN configuration strings lengths

comments.message: Instead of using xxx_MAX_LEN+1 everywhere, you should add a new define xxx_MAX_BYTES

not sure that it's needed
le_mdc_GetAPN calls le_utf8_Copy which checks \0 from data, not from length
we're expecting 50 bytes for the apn + 1 for the null character

Yes I know
But check le_utf8_Copy API code

le_result_t le_utf8_Copy
(
char *destStr,
const char *srcStr,
const size_t destSize,
size_t *numBytesPtr 
)
		
Copies the string in srcStr to the start of destStr and returns the number of bytes copied (not including the NULL-terminator) in numBytesPtr. Null can be passed into numBytesPtr if the number of bytes copied is not needed. The srcStr must be in UTF-8 format.

If the size of srcStr is less than or equal to the destination buffer size then the entire srcStr will be copied including the null-character. The rest of the destination buffer is not modified.

If the size of srcStr is larger than the destination buffer then the maximum number of characters (from srcStr) plus a null-character that will fit in the destination buffer is copied.

UTF-8 characters may be more than one byte long and this function will only copy whole characters not partial characters. Therefore, even if srcStr is larger than the destination buffer, the copied characters may not fill the entire destination buffer because the last character copied may not align exactly with the end of the destination buffer.

The destination string will always be Null-terminated, unless destSize is zero.

If destStr and srcStr overlap the behaviour of this function is undefined.

Returns
LE_OK if srcStr was completely copied to the destStr.
LE_OVERFLOW if srcStr was truncated when it was copied to destStr.
Parameters
[in]	destStr	Destination where the srcStr is to be copied.
[in]	srcStr	UTF-8 source string.
[in]	destSize	Size of the destination buffer in bytes.
[out]	numBytesPtr	Number of bytes copied not including the NULL-terminator. Parameter can be set to NULL if the number of bytes copied is not needed.
I agree with Riadh, this should be 50+1
I would prefer APN_MAX_LEN+1 instead of 51

comments.message:

commits.commitMessage:
Get Current HTTP response code

Resolves: LE-7365
Change-Id: I4e51b3e7a10bb056747807f736dc32cd45d4def9
commits.subject: Get Current HTTP response code

comments.message:
according to the specs, we should check that a session was made before returning the response code otherwise we return Ok.

P.S: Note at the end of page 14

Hi Riadh, this logic would cover that scenario as well, no? The way I read the spec if a session is connected & package download initiated once we can read the status of that download even after closing the session. 

If we really need to be in an active session to get the download status, I can do...

    if ((httpStatus != LE_AVC_HTTP_STATUS_INVALID)
        &&(statusPtr->session == SESSION_STATUS_UP))

Hi Prushothaman,

I think that we can return LE_AVC_HTTP_STATUS_INVALID, it's a status after all (for me it means that we couldn't get the download response code ==> check logs).

What I understood from the specs (it's not very clear) is that if the session is down then at+wdse return Ok else response code.

There is also this part of the specs that needs to be handled

> Notes
> This command returns +CME ERROR: 3 when:
> - a parameter is filled
  this one is already implemented.
 
> - the Device services are not in ACTIVATED state
> (see +WDSG command  for more information)
not yet implemented
ok. Agree to return download status only when session is open. But passing LE_AVC_HTTP_STATUS_INVALID might confuse user as this is not a valid http response code.

we should check if the services are activated otherwise at+wdse has to return +CME ERROR: 3

This is how I understood the specs.

 if services are not activated
 then return +CME ERROR: 3

 if session is down
 then return OK

 return HTTP response code
ok. Agreed to send an error code when session is not open. But, we shouldn't send http response code invalid.

I would rather change if (statusPtr->session != SESSION_STATUS_DOWN) to if (statusPtr->session == SESSION_STATUS_DOWN) in the current patch.

I don't see a reason to check credential status for this condition.In what you proposed you are returning a OK  when session is down. From our earlier discussion, you suggested to send +CME error when session is down.

Hi Prushothaman,

I think that there is a misunderstanding here. I've never said that. Do you have a copy of the specs ?

According to the specs:

> *Description
> This Sierra Wireless proprietary command allows a user to 
> know the last HTTP(S) response received by the device for 
> the package download.

> *Syntax

> -Action command
> AT+WDSE
> [+WDSE: <HTTP_Status>]
> OK
> -Read command
> None
> -Test command
> None

> *Parameters and Defined Values
> Last HTTP response received by the embedded module
> If HTTP/HTTPS is not yet used, the command only return OK

> *Notes
> If no session was made with the server, AT+WDSE only
> returns with OK response, without any
> +WDSE <HTTP_Status> > response.
> This command returns +CME ERROR: 3 when:
> -a parameter is filled 
> -the Device services are not in ACTIVATED state
> (see +WDSG command  for more information)
Sorry, the notes is what I missed. Thanks for clarifying!

They are defined in le_avc.api so it would be best to use LE_AVC_POLLING_TIMER_MAX_VAL, LE_AVC_RETRY_TIMER_MAX_VAL, and LE_AVC_NUM_RETRY_TIMERS.

You are right - those other two defines aren't there yet but will be soon.  They are in this review I am working on now: https://gerrit-legato/#/c/15601/3
